Subject: [PATCH] refactor: consolidate instrument-symbol resolution onto a
 single source
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Following up on fix/instrument-map-legacy-fallback: reconciler.py had its
own, fully independent instrument_id->symbol resolution path
(_load_instrument_map() + a hand-maintained _FALLBACK_INSTRUMENT_MAP
dict), duplicating logic already present in bot.api.instruments.
get_instrument_map() and diverging from what data_worker uses.

_FALLBACK_INSTRUMENT_MAP's own comments documented a history of past
errors ("was wrongly NVDA/TSLA — confirmed MSFT", "was wrongly XRP-USD!")
— exactly the kind of silent drift a hardcoded, manually-updated dict has
no mechanism to catch when it goes stale again. It also couldn't benefit
from any of the corrections made via scripts/audit_instrument_symbols.py
or manual fixes (e.g. NATGAS instrument_id=22) unless someone remembered
to update this second copy by hand too.

Removed:
  - _FALLBACK_INSTRUMENT_MAP (29-entry hardcoded dict)
  - _load_instrument_map() (duplicate JSON-loading logic)

Changed:
  - reconciler.py now imports and calls bot.api.instruments.
    get_instrument_map(client=client) directly — the same function
    data_worker uses, with the same file-cache -> trading.db
    `instruments` table -> legacy-DB -> empty fallback chain from the
    previous fix.

Unchanged: _resolve_symbol()'s 3-tier lookup (local map -> live API ->
UNKNOWN) is untouched — it already works generically over whatever map
it's handed, Tier 2's live API call remains the safety net for anything
not yet in the DB.

Trade-off worth noting: on a truly fresh install (empty `instruments`
table, no cache file yet), get_instrument_map() now returns {} instead
of the ~29 hardcoded entries the old fallback guaranteed. In practice
this window is narrow — discovery_worker's _ensure_instrument() populates
the `instruments` table before any trade can exist, and reconciler has
nothing to reconcile before the first position exists anyway. Flagging
this explicitly rather than silently accepting the behavior change.

Verified: 59/59 tests pass. Manually traced client lifecycle — the
instrument_map resolution call sits before all client.close() calls in
the success path, matching the existing "close only after all API
lookups complete" ordering from the 3-tier resolution commit.
